{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NLSbdo5mWZ9DSCPaFZji5s","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This requires multiple modules interacting — AI vision model classifies image, then the pipeline decides to hold vs. publish. The failure could be in the AI model classification or the pipeline routing.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on OS/network/subprocess? The real question is whether the AI vision model needs to be real.\n- LLM-DEP: Does correctness depend on what a real AI vision model produces? YES — if you mock the AI model to return \"explicit\", you're testing the pipeline routing, not whether the AI actually detects explicit content. \n\nTo verify the image is actually flagged, I need the real AI model to classify it as explicit—the behavior's correctness hinges on the model working properly. This is a single classification step followed by a routing decision, so the minimum level is **Agentic** — the real AI vision model must correctly identify explicit content.\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).**\n\nThe text AI model needs to handle obfuscation robustly, so I'm checking whether mocking it would miss the real challenge—which is whether the model can actually detect hate speech through these evasion techniques.  This is a quality claim about adversarial robustness, not just routing logic, so it's **Agentic** — I need the real model to verify it catches obfuscated hate speech.\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\nHere the focus shifts to pipeline routing logic—after both checks return \"pass\", does the system actually publish? I can mock both AI models to return \"pass\" and verify the downstream routing works correctly, since the correctness is about the pipeline logic itself, not the AI quality.\n\n**Behavior 4: The full moderation pipeline completes within 5 seconds of submission.**\n\nThis is a latency requirement that depends on real infrastructure—actual AI model response times, network latency, and queue processing all factor into whether the 5-second SLA holds. The end-to-end timing can't be accurately tested without real components in the loop.\n\nThe pipeline involves multiple sequential agentic steps (image check, then text check, then publish decision), so this crosses into **Workflow** territory. If I mock the AI models, the timing test becomes meaningless since I'd always hit the target. I need the real pipeline running with actual model calls to measure whether the system truly meets the performance requirement.\n\nFor the retry behavior when the vision model is unavailable, I can test this with integration fakes — mocking the AI model to throw an exception and verifying the retry queue captures the post correctly. This doesn't require real infrastructure or depend on actual model quality, just the error handling logic across the AI call and queue modules.\n\nNow looking at borderline image consistency — this is fundamentally about AI non-determinism. Borderline cases are exactly where LLMs vary most, so running the same image through multiple times will likely produce different moderation decisions. This directly tests whether the system handles that variability, which means I need the real model dependency to see if consistency actually holds. I'm settling on **Agentic** for the consistency test since it's really just running the same classification multiple times to verify the model's behavior, not a sequential pipeline where outputs feed into the next step. Now let me compile the full breakdown of all six test cases with their classifications and reasoning. abilities.\n\nFor behavior 4 (timing), let me reconsider. The behavior says \"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.\" \n\nThis is a performance/latency test. The key question is: does this require real AI calls?\n- If you mock AI calls to be instant, the test would always pass but wouldn't reflect real performance.\n- The 5-second SLA during \"peak hours\" (high throughput) suggests this needs real infrastructure.\n- It's a full pipeline test with real AI calls → multiple agentic steps → Workflow.\n\nBut could it be System? System is \"subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, or real external API call.\" The AI models are real external API calls... but the level LLM-DEP specifically captures \"real AI/ML model call.\" So if it requires real AI calls + timing, it's at least Agentic with multiple sequential steps, making it Workflow.\n\nFor behavior 6, I need to distinguish between Workflow and Agentic more carefully. Submitting the same image multiple times means multiple independent calls to the same agentic step, not a sequence of different steps. That's testing the AI model's consistency through repeated invocations, which is Agentic rather than Workflow.\n\nSo my final categorization is: Agentic, Agentic, Integration, Workflow, Integration, Agentic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9738,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9738},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7821cb1-8868-4188-a6c9-113d4b60ad62","uuid":"1d2dc1ad-67dd-460a-b9f9-724bae59dfdb"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NLSbdo5mWZ9DSCPaFZji5s","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012XKvQzZNucJXcbSr8xrefp","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The behavior's correctness claim is that the AI vision model correctly classifies explicit content. Mocking the model to return 'explicit' trivially passes the routing logic but never tests whether the model actually detects the content. The failure mode is in AI classification quality, not pipeline wiring. REJECTION-GATE: Integration is disqualified because an in-process fake that always returns 'explicit' proves nothing about whether the real model flags the image. System is disqualified because there is no OS/subprocess dependency — the test boundary is the AI model's output, not network infrastructure.","test_description":"Submit a set of real images containing explicit content to the live AI vision model endpoint. Verify that the moderation service receives a 'flagged' classification from the model and routes each post to the human-review hold queue rather than publishing it.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Regardless of obfuscation techniques' is an adversarial robustness claim about the real AI text model's classification quality. Mocking the model to return 'hate speech' for obfuscated input would trivially pass and test nothing. The actual failure is that the real model might not detect h4te $pe3ch or unicode-lookalike variants — this only surfaces with the real model. REJECTION-GATE: Integration is disqualified because the failure does not lie at a module-to-module handoff; it lies in what the AI model produces when given obfuscated input.","test_description":"Submit a corpus of hate speech text in multiple obfuscated forms (letter substitution, unicode lookalikes, spacing variations) to the live AI text model. Assert that every variant returns a flagged classification and is routed to the human-review hold queue.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.77,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode here is in the pipeline routing logic: does the system correctly publish when both checks return 'pass'? This is a module-boundary failure between the decision aggregator and the publish action. The AI models can be stubbed to return clean results — correctness does not depend on what a real model produces. LLM-DEP: No — the behavior tests post-classification routing, not classification quality. REAL-INFRA: An in-process fake publisher is sufficient to detect a silent-drop or erroneous hold. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic is disqualified because the behavior does not assert anything about what the AI model classifies; it asserts only the routing logic after both models return clean.","test_description":"Wire together the image-check module, text-check module, and publish-decision module with stubbed AI models that return clean results. Submit a post and assert it reaches the publish path, not the hold queue and not silently discarded.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The pipeline explicitly involves multiple sequential agentic steps: image classification by an AI vision model, then text classification by an AI text model, then publish decision. REAL-INFRA: Mocking the AI calls to be instant would make any timing budget trivially pass; real latency only appears with real model calls. LLM-DEP: Real AI/ML model calls are required to produce meaningful latency measurements. REJECTION-GATE: System is disqualified because the bottleneck is AI model call latency, not OS/subprocess/HTTP infrastructure alone — mocked HTTP stubs would hide model latency. Agentic is disqualified because this requires two real agentic steps (vision + text) in sequence before the timing assertion can be made.","test_description":"Submit a post containing both an image and text to the full live pipeline (real AI vision model + real AI text model + publish decision). Record wall-clock time from submission receipt to publish/hold decision and assert it is under 5 seconds. Run under simulated concurrent load to represent peak-hour conditions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.14,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the module boundary between the AI client and the error-handling/retry-queue module. When the AI client throws an unavailability exception, does the orchestrator enqueue for retry or fall through to auto-approve? This is a code-path and state-propagation failure that shows up when the error path is exercised. LLM-DEP: No — the AI model need not be real; the test stubs it to raise an unavailability error. REAL-INFRA: An in-process fake queue is sufficient to verify the enqueue behavior; no real message broker is needed for this logic check. REJECTION-GATE: System is disqualified because the unavailability can be faithfully reproduced by a stub that raises an exception — no real network or subprocess is required.","test_description":"Configure the AI vision model client stub to raise a service-unavailable error. Submit an image post and assert it appears in the retry queue and is not marked as approved or published. Verify the retry queue entry contains the original post data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Borderline inputs are exactly where AI model non-determinism is highest. Consistency across repeated submissions is a direct property of the real model's stochastic behavior — it cannot be tested with a deterministic mock that always returns the same canned value. Running this test against the real model 100 times may yield different outcomes, which is the failure the behavior is designed to catch. MOCK-HIDE: Any mock would produce identical output every call, making a consistency test vacuously pass. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow is disqualified because each submission is an independent invocation of the same single agentic step, not a sequence of different agentic steps feeding each other. The multiple calls are the test harness structure, not a multi-step pipeline.","test_description":"Identify a set of images that are borderline by submitting them once and recording the classification score near the decision threshold. Submit each borderline image N times (e.g., 5) to the live AI vision model within a short time window. Assert that all N decisions for each image are identical (all flagged or all clean). Log any inconsistencies as test failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.18}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9738,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9738},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7821cb1-8868-4188-a6c9-113d4b60ad62","uuid":"3101ee57-83f1-4b18-81c2-04efbc103d34"}
